1 (10) the languages in which grant applications, agreements, guidelines,
2 technical support, training, and professional development are offered and whether the
3 languages offered align with those spoken by potential private prekindergarten providers;
4 (11) the languages in which materials provided to parents of children
5 enrolled with a private prekindergarten provider are offered and whether the languages
6 offered align with those spoken by the parents; and
7 (12) opportunities to pool resources among private prekindergarten
8 providers, including employee benefits, creating a centralized substitute teacher pool, and
9 other benefits that might come from economies of scale;
10 (13) challenges for public prekindergarten providers in building or adapting
11 facilities to accommodate prekindergarten students; and
12 (14) how best to use publicly funded prekindergarten to provide a quality
13 early childhood education for students with and without disabilities together in the same
14 classrooms, including by developing methods to best:
15 (i) combine federal, State, and local funding sources available for
16 children in a publicly funded prekindergarten context to maximize support for all children;
17 (ii) improve teacher and staff training and recruitment to address
18 the needs of students with and without disabilities; and
19 (iii) foster collaboration between public and private prekindergarten
20 providers in delivering specialized transportation and services for students with
21 disabilities.
22 (c) In conducting the analysis required under subsection (a) of this section, the
23 Council shall solicit feedback from public prekindergarten providers, private
24 prekindergarten providers, and child care providers who have elected not to participate in
25 the publicly funded prekindergarten program.
26 (d) (1) The Council may consult additional subject matter and policy experts
27 that the Council determines are beneficial in conducting the analysis.
28 (2) The Council may establish subcommittees to carry out the analysis
29 required under this section.
30 (e) (1) On or before June 1, 2026, the Council shall submit to the State Board
31 of Education and, in accordance with § 2–1257 of the State Government Article, the General
32 Assembly, an interim report on the results of its analysis, including recommendations for
33 changes to regulations, policies, and procedures to increase the efficacy of the publicly
34 funded prekindergarten program and to make the program more equitable for providers
35 and families.

